title: For Sale/Trade:  STOP OVER PRICING YOUR GUNS
postcontent: Wake up people, if your gun is worth x amount for a cash sale its not magically worth a bunch more just because you trade it!...your $500 glock isnt worth more just because you trade it.  Also, remember that just beacuse you paid a million dollars for your boat anchor 1911 doesnt mean that is what its value is.  You might think its worth that much but you have to consider the WHOLE market.  That 1200-1300 Kimber that you list and relist and relist isnt selling because you can buy it all over the place for 1000.  Again, just because you over paid for it doesnt mean thats what its worth...and it definitely isnt worth even more just because you're trading it.  Only a moron would trade you 200 over value for something.  At that point they could jusy go buy a new one and have money left over

title: For Sale/Trade:  Built Remington 700P
postcontent:
Custom Remington 700P
This rifle has many upgrades and is a fine piece of equipment, rifle started as an older 700P with a glass and aluminum bedded HS Precision stock. I upgraded to the KRG chassis to give it a little more weight and adjustability. Rifle shoots 1 MOA all day long. Bore is clean and has plenty of life, do not know the shot count but .308 barrels are generally good for around 3,500-5,000 rounds. I doubt it even close to that based on the tight groups achieved with the rifle. The action itself shows (little) pitting from the previous owners neglect but it's really not noticeable. The shot cycle is VERY manageable nothing comparable to a .308 deer rifle. The muzzlebrake makes this a sweet shooter.
      I have shot multiple loads through this gun and all perform very well. Inc. hornaday whitetail classic, fusion, S&B, Remington, and hand loads. I did notice some pressure issues when shooting 200grn projectiles. Bolt got a little sticky on cycling but everything under 175gr runs flawlessly. Trigger is stock never changed it because I never thought it needed a new one. Once again this is a serious built precision rifle and anyone who wishes to own it will have no doubts. Message me for any pics or questions.

The Tokarev typically chambers the powerful 7.62x25mm bottleneck cartridge. The Chinese made a unique variant chambered in 9mm—the Norinco 213— for the civilian market. The State Factory 66-manufactured all-steel 213 is nearly identical to the Russian TT-33 Tokarev with one key difference: an additional frame mounted safety.
